1. Why should you use a version control tool?

	In the repository multiple developers commit their code frequently. There is a possibility that a newly developed unit can affect another existing unit.
  Version control tool records every changes made in the  repository and  tracks the part of the code which caused the defect.	

2. Which of the following correctly describes what a unit test is

	It is a level of software testing where the individual units are tested.
	Unit tests usually involve asserting the final output against the expected output using the inputs provided as part of the tests.

3. What are the various build tools used in Java?

	Apache Ant, Apache Maven, Gradle

4. One of your projects fail compilation errors due to missing JAR files that are needed for your project. Which of the following tools can help to fix the errors

	Apache Ant, Apache Maven

5. What is meant by a "commit" in a version control Tool?
	
	Commit maintains the history of changes made by the developer in the source repository as versions.

6. Which utility can be used to move deployment packages across servers;

	SSH

7. How is system testing different from unit testing and Integration testing?

	System testing is done to test whether a completely developed feature perform according to its requirements whereas unit testing is done to check whether 
  the granular modules in the system perform well. Integration testing is done to check whether different systems when integrated together perform its intended functions
  without breaking one another.

8. What are the some of the metrics that are measured/evaluated during a performance testing phase?
	
  Response time, Load balance, Withstanding Stress.

9. What is meant by Regression testing?

	It is done to verify that a newly added feature in an application has not affected the already existing features of the application.



 
